  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "What is the pigeonhole principle? Give three non-trivial applications.",
  "response_text": "The pigeonhole principle is a fundamental concept in combinatorics and mathematics that states that if n items are put into m containers, with n > m, then at least one container must contain more than one item. In other words, if you have more items than containers, some container will inevitably be overfilled.\n\nHere are three non-trivial applications of the pigeonhole principle:\n\n1. **Error Detection in Data Transmission**: In digital communication, data is often transmitted in packets. If there are more packets than slots available in a transmission buffer, the pigeonhole principle implies that at least one slot must contain more than one packet. This can lead to errors in data transmission, as the extra packet may be lost or corrupted. This principle is used in error detection and correction algorithms to ensure reliable data transmission.\n\n2. **Scheduling Conflicts**: In scheduling problems, the pigeonhole principle can be used to show that if there are more tasks than time slots available, at least two tasks must be scheduled at the same time. This can lead to conflicts and inefficiencies in the schedule. For example, in a university course schedule, if there are more courses than available time slots, some courses must be scheduled at the same time, leading to conflicts for students.\n\n3. **Social Network Analysis**: In social network analysis, the pigeonhole principle can be used to show that if there are more people than groups in a social network, at least two people must be in the same group. This can be used to identify clusters or communities within a social network. For example, in a company with more employees than departments, at least two employees must work in the same department.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 8\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 6\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
